<br>
Let's review a couple of other recent incidents where US military mistakes killed people:<br>
<br>
-A couple of years ago, you may remember a US Marine pilot killed two dozen people in a cablecar in the Alps because he was &quot;hot-rodding.&quot; His tailfin severed the cable car's line and the occupants fell over a thousand feet to their deaths. That Marine was convicted and sent to prison. <br>
<br>
-Last year a US Navy submarine capsized a Japanese fishing trawler, drowning several people. The captain of the vessel, with whom the error clearly lay, received a &quot;letter of reprimand&quot; that ended his military career. No criminal action was filed against him, however. <br>
<br>
My point? Military accidents happen. In fact, they are frequent. It's a dangerous job with no room for errors in communication or judgement. But we are all human, and even the most well-trained personnel make mistakes. In the military, mistakes kill people. What happened last night was a tragedy, but we don't have the facts yet. Don't judge. <br>
